Hot buttered rum is a warm and comforting alcoholic beverage typically made with dark rum, butter, brown sugar, and warm spices such as cinnamon, nutmeg, and cloves. The drink is often served during the winter months and is a popular holiday beverage in many countries.
To make hot buttered rum, the butter, brown sugar, and spices are first combined to make a mixture that is then added to hot water or
cider. The rum is then stirred in, and the drink is served hot with a garnish of cinnamon or a cinnamon stick.
Hot buttered rum has a rich, creamy texture and a sweet and spicy flavor that is perfect for warming up on a cold day. The butter and spices give the drink a comforting aroma, while the rum adds a subtle kick of alcohol.
While hot buttered rum is a traditional holiday drink, it can also be enjoyed at any time during the winter months. It is often served at holiday parties and gatherings, but can also be made at home for a cozy night In.

A solitary figure stands in three-quarter profile against a dark, textured backdrop that resembles aged canvas or smoke-stained walls. The head is covered by a long-beaked plague mask, its surface cracked and weathered, bone-colored with darker stains embedded into the grain. The hollow eye sockets are deep and opaque, offering no reflection, giving the impression of an empty gaze fixed on something beyond the frame.

The figure wears layered, heavy robes in muted tones of rust, umber, and blackened red. The fabric appears thick and timeworn, with frayed edges and uneven coloration, as though soaked repeatedly by years of exposure and ritual use. A hood drapes over the head, blending into the shoulders and further obscuring any trace of a human form beneath the garments.

Hands emerge from the sleeves and are folded calmly at chest level. They are pale and skeletal in appearance, fingers long and rigid, resting with deliberate stillness rather than tension. The lighting is soft but directional, illuminating the beak and upper torso while allowing the lower body to dissolve gradually into shadow.

The atmosphere is solemn and historical, evoking isolation, endurance, and silent duty. There is no sense of motion, only presence, as if the figure has stood in this position for centuries, observing cycles of illness, fear, and survival without comment.
